Speed up from 177s to 152s.

Remove loop that was checking each error individually against allowlist regexps one by one. This is slow and also results in the same line being reported multiple times (e.g., for a total of 254 pylint reports, there are 1356 matches printed).

Furthermore, loop seems to have matched real errors against the approved list (because it takes regexps as words, not as lines! -- see below), thus allowing linting errors to pass through. Fixing them in this change too.

```
Found an allowlisted error:
  tensorflow/security/fuzzing/raggedCountSparseOutput_fuzz.py:36: [C0330(bad-continuation), ] Wrong hanging indentation (remove 6 spaces).
  via space
      ^^^^^ (this is a word in a allowlist line, taken as a regexp to match)
```

Display proper statistics about the errors at the end of the step.

Part of the work for #46046, #43040. Unblocks #46075

P6.

A different PR makes additional changes to be able to build all the
kernels for the Vision P6 but this change was separated out into its own
PR to keep individual PRs smaller and focused.

Tested:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=Google_F1 test_keyword_benchmark -j8
```

Gives:
```
InitializeKeywordRunner() took 239589 ticks (239 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(1) took 171203 ticks (171 ms)
KeywordRunNIerations(10) took 1711501 ticks (1711 ms)
```

This is a small increase in the latency but is not important since we
are still only using the reference implementation.

And the kernel test passes for fusion_f1i (13 cases) and hifimini (2 cases):

```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile TARGET=xtensa OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=xtensa TARGET_ARCH=fusion_f1 XTENSA_CORE=Google_F1 test_kernel_quantize_test -j8

Previously the state migration process was using the fallback strict
error check when migrating to or from a Terraform Cloud workspace. This
resulted in an error when running init if the local and remote Terraform
versions did not exactly match.

This was excessively strict. When migrating from a remote Terraform
Cloud workspace to local state, there is no need for a version check at
all, as we cannot break the Terraform Cloud workspace. When migrating
to Terraform Cloud, we should use the more forgiving check, rather than
the strict equality.

This commit fixes both of these cases accordingly, and allows migrating
state to and from Terraform Cloud remote workspaces without errors.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njuCZ/terraform/commits/212a97c3bdf1cce82d1ca14b91e4f79c176a9818"},{"sha":"44daf76624c6445ff82d0634b1e00091b579db68","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"remove InitProvisioner and close all at once

InitProvisioner only stored the provisioner in the cache and provided a
way to return an error. We can push this back further into the cli init
process, but for now we can move the error into the Provisioner call and
drop InitProvisioner.

This also changes CloseProvisioner to CloseProvisioners, in preparation
for the removal of the graph nodes.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njuCZ/terraform/commits/44daf76624c6445ff82d0634b1e00091b579db68"},{"sha":"a6db207b8772cc874723b4d8100c9e19a51a8a3e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"remove provisioner graph nodes

Provisioners are always run via a single instance, and their

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/afe1e4e9a1d4ef1b06bf96e9351f1a9e70f1029a"},{"sha":"f4b686b5f3db28f09d2561eb2aee3e1c3a9bf270","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26614 from hashicorp/jbardin/0.14-26606

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

Note that we do not suppress logs if connection info contains sensitive
information, as provisioners should not be logging connection
information under any circumstances.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/47f8ed4cd62068332eca4d1903b7dfaf6064adc4"},{"sha":"2b485cd4284725396abe26b5ae0175659199e78a","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"website: Sensitive values in provisioner config","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/2b485cd4284725396abe26b5ae0175659199e78a"},{"sha":"a18415686b40d89406992d5d300dc02566a91c4c","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26630 from hashicorp/alisdair/sensitive-values-provisioners-014

The Legacy SDK cannot handle missing strings from objects in sets, and
will insert an empty string when planning the missing value. This
subverts the `couldHaveUnknownBlockPlaceholder` check, and causes
errors when `dynamic` is used with NestingSet blocks.

We don't have a separate codepath to handle the internals of
AssertObjectCompatible differently for the legacy SDK, but we can treat
empty strings as null strings within set objects to avoid the failed
assertions.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/060f8acc081c9be2ef5b2d0277742ea753615ee2"},{"sha":"527f3e654cfd2417410ae4bdeffecfa53d28ea7b","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26641 from hashicorp/jbardin/backport-26638

[{"sha":"142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Add TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize integration test

This test validates that `RUN` and `COPY` both target a read-write
sandbox on Windows that is configured according to the daemon's
`storage-opts` setting.

Sadly, this is a slow test, so we need to bump the timeout to 60 minutes
from the default of 10 minutes.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dk-cpa-68/moby/commits/142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68"},{"sha":"56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Apply a 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size globally

This applies the 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size to not just `RUN` under
`docker build` (as was previously the case) but to `COPY` and `ADD`
under `docker build` and also to `docker run`.

It also removes an inconsistency that the 127GB size was not applied
when `--platform windows` was not passed to `docker build`, but WCOW was
still used as a platform default, e.g. Docker Desktop for Windows in
Windows Containers mode.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dk-cpa-68/moby/commits/56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296"},{"sha":"db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Parse storage-opt in GraphDriver init on Windows

This ensures the storage-opts applies to all operations by the graph
drivers, replacing the merging of storage-opts into container storage
config at container-creation time, and hence applying storage-opts to
non-container operations like `COPY` and `ADD` in the builder.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dk-cpa-68/moby/commits/db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32"},{"sha":"695b151a18299ade7c70dfe3babc8d77b7f5aba6","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Work around small disk on Windows-RS5 CI nodes

The free disk space on the Windows RS5 CI nodes appears to be just the
right size that the TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize test can generate 21GB of
layers, and then a 21GB sandbox inside a container, and then runs out of
space while committing the layer.

Helpfully, this failure is distinguishable in the logs from a failure
when the sandbox is too small, so we can do that.

TODO: Revert this if-and-when the Windows-RS5 CI nodes have more free
space.

## Motivation

An *interleaved* update is one that is scheduled while a render is
already in progress, typically from a concurrent user input event.

We have to take care not to process these updates during the current
render, because a multiple interleaved updates may have been scheduled
across many components; to avoid tearing, we cannot render some of
those updates without rendering all of them.

## Old approach

What we currently do when we detect an interleaved update is assign a
lane that is not part of the current render.

This has some unfortunate drawbacks. For example, we will eventually run
out of lanes at a given priority level. When this happens, our last
resort is to interrupt the current render and start over from scratch.
If this happens enough, it can lead to starvation.

More concerning, there are a suprising number of places that must
separately account for this case, often in subtle ways. The maintenance
complexity has led to a number of tearing bugs.

## New approach

I added a new field to the update queue, `interleaved`. It's a linked
list, just like the `pending` field. When an interleaved update is
scheduled, we add it to the `interleaved` list instead of `pending`.

Then we push the entire queue object onto a global array. When the
current render exits, we iterate through the array of interleaved queues
and transfer the `interleaved` list to the `pending` list.

So, until the current render has exited (whether due to a commit or an
interruption), it's impossible to process an interleaved update, because
they have not yet been enqueued.

In this new approach, we don't need to resort to clever lanes tricks to
avoid inconsistencies. This should allow us to simplify a lot of the
logic that's currently in ReactFiberWorkLoop and ReactFiberLane,
especially `findUpdateLane` and `getNextLanes`. All the logic for
interleaved updates is isolated to one place.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mahak/react/commits/f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee"}]

If provisioner configuration or connection info includes sensitive

Unlike resources, we do not need to capture marked paths here, so we

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

Note that we do not suppress logs if connection info contains sensitive
information, as provisioners should not be logging connection
information under any circumstances.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/4f53234d8cf6c9f964ac8bfa8bce3a624a119bf1"},{"sha":"e3804810a9c95fe590f6eb3807a12d86a0ecf76e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Accept JSON encoded dynamic values from providers

Core was previously ignoring JSON-encoded dynamic values, but these are
technically supported, so we must either error or accept the value.
Since we already have the decoder for Json state, it's minimal effort to
support this on all plugin methods too.

This change also gives providers an easy way to implement the
UpgradeResourceState method. The obvious implementation of returning the same
JSON-encoded value has tripped up a few providers not using the legacy
SDK already, and we should have at least indicated that the value was
being lost.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/e3804810a9c95fe590f6eb3807a12d86a0ecf76e"},{"sha":"98dc3990628bb94f5877cd04e1cf56851ba8a7bb","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26606 from hashicorp/jbardin/proposed-set-comparison

More precise handling of lists and maps within sets for ProposedNewObject","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/98dc3990628bb94f5877cd04e1cf56851ba8a7bb"},{"sha":"30204ecded21fb52c992b0a707bb4cbb96e2c608","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/cliconfig: Allow development overrides for providers

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/30204ecded21fb52c992b0a707bb4cbb96e2c608"}]

Speed up from 177s to 152s.

Remove loop that was checking each error individually against allowlist regexps one by one. This is slow and also results in the same line being reported multiple times (e.g., for a total of 254 pylint reports, there are 1356 matches printed).

Furthermore, loop seems to have matched real errors against the approved list (because it takes regexps as words, not as lines! -- see below), thus allowing linting errors to pass through. Fixing them in this change too.

```
Found an allowlisted error:
  tensorflow/security/fuzzing/raggedCountSparseOutput_fuzz.py:36: [C0330(bad-continuation), ] Wrong hanging indentation (remove 6 spaces).
  via space
      ^^^^^ (this is a word in a allowlist line, taken as a regexp to match)
```

Display proper statistics about the errors at the end of the step.

Part of the work for #46046, #43040. Unblocks #46075

[{"sha":"142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Add TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize integration test

This test validates that `RUN` and `COPY` both target a read-write
sandbox on Windows that is configured according to the daemon's
`storage-opts` setting.

Sadly, this is a slow test, so we need to bump the timeout to 60 minutes
from the default of 10 minutes.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tfl0pz/moby/commits/142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68"},{"sha":"56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Apply a 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size globally

This applies the 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size to not just `RUN` under
`docker build` (as was previously the case) but to `COPY` and `ADD`
under `docker build` and also to `docker run`.

It also removes an inconsistency that the 127GB size was not applied
when `--platform windows` was not passed to `docker build`, but WCOW was
still used as a platform default, e.g. Docker Desktop for Windows in
Windows Containers mode.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tfl0pz/moby/commits/56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296"},{"sha":"db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Parse storage-opt in GraphDriver init on Windows

This ensures the storage-opts applies to all operations by the graph
drivers, replacing the merging of storage-opts into container storage
config at container-creation time, and hence applying storage-opts to
non-container operations like `COPY` and `ADD` in the builder.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tfl0pz/moby/commits/db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32"},{"sha":"695b151a18299ade7c70dfe3babc8d77b7f5aba6","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Work around small disk on Windows-RS5 CI nodes

The free disk space on the Windows RS5 CI nodes appears to be just the
right size that the TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize test can generate 21GB of
layers, and then a 21GB sandbox inside a container, and then runs out of
space while committing the layer.

Helpfully, this failure is distinguishable in the logs from a failure
when the sandbox is too small, so we can do that.

TODO: Revert this if-and-when the Windows-RS5 CI nodes have more free
space.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tfl0pz/moby/commits/695b151a18299ade7c70dfe3babc8d77b7f5aba6"},{"sha":"1571e9331b4c56cc350bdf339b9aacd72eb3bbbd","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Use specific APIs for shared mount-point behaviour

PiperOrigin-RevId: 353677319
Change-Id: I3d0d7da8602ab45bbfa6fb23dc54b68cc7ea2ef7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/74e741619f700d8533d0925de5f566999a1ff62e"},{"sha":"fbf6fed2c7532fb673dcdbc97b28a1a8d13f8d0c","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"Refactor and speed up pylint code by ~15%.

Speed up from 177s to 152s.

Remove loop that was checking each error individually against allowlist regexps one by one. This is slow and also results in the same line being reported multiple times (e.g., for a total of 254 pylint reports, there are 1356 matches printed).

Furthermore, loop seems to have matched real errors against the approved list (because it takes regexps as words, not as lines! -- see below), thus allowing linting errors to pass through. Fixing them in this change too.

```
Found an allowlisted error:
  tensorflow/security/fuzzing/raggedCountSparseOutput_fuzz.py:36: [C0330(bad-continuation), ] Wrong hanging indentation (remove 6 spaces).
  via space
      ^^^^^ (this is a word in a allowlist line, taken as a regexp to match)
```

Display proper statistics about the errors at the end of the step.

Part of the work for #46046, #43040. Unblocks #46075

PiperOrigin-RevId: 353677319
Change-Id: I3d0d7da8602ab45bbfa6fb23dc54b68cc7ea2ef7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/74e741619f700d8533d0925de5f566999a1ff62e"},{"sha":"fbf6fed2c7532fb673dcdbc97b28a1a8d13f8d0c","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"Refactor and speed up pylint code by ~15%.

Speed up from 177s to 152s.

Remove loop that was checking each error individually against allowlist regexps one by one. This is slow and also results in the same line being reported multiple times (e.g., for a total of 254 pylint reports, there are 1356 matches printed).

Furthermore, loop seems to have matched real errors against the approved list (because it takes regexps as words, not as lines! -- see below), thus allowing linting errors to pass through. Fixing them in this change too.

```
Found an allowlisted error:
  tensorflow/security/fuzzing/raggedCountSparseOutput_fuzz.py:36: [C0330(bad-continuation), ] Wrong hanging indentation (remove 6 spaces).
  via space
      ^^^^^ (this is a word in a allowlist line, taken as a regexp to match)
```

Display proper statistics about the errors at the end of the step.

Part of the work for #46046, #43040. Unblocks #46075

PiperOrigin-RevId: 353677319
Change-Id: I3d0d7da8602ab45bbfa6fb23dc54b68cc7ea2ef7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KabirKwatra/tensorflow/commits/74e741619f700d8533d0925de5f566999a1ff62e"},{"sha":"fbf6fed2c7532fb673dcdbc97b28a1a8d13f8d0c","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"Refactor and speed up pylint code by ~15%.

Speed up from 177s to 152s.

Remove loop that was checking each error individually against allowlist regexps one by one. This is slow and also results in the same line being reported multiple times (e.g., for a total of 254 pylint reports, there are 1356 matches printed).

Furthermore, loop seems to have matched real errors against the approved list (because it takes regexps as words, not as lines! -- see below), thus allowing linting errors to pass through. Fixing them in this change too.

```
Found an allowlisted error:
  tensorflow/security/fuzzing/raggedCountSparseOutput_fuzz.py:36: [C0330(bad-continuation), ] Wrong hanging indentation (remove 6 spaces).
  via space
      ^^^^^ (this is a word in a allowlist line, taken as a regexp to match)
```

Display proper statistics about the errors at the end of the step.

Part of the work for #46046, #43040. Unblocks #46075

[{"sha":"142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Add TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize integration test

This test validates that `RUN` and `COPY` both target a read-write
sandbox on Windows that is configured according to the daemon's
`storage-opts` setting.

Sadly, this is a slow test, so we need to bump the timeout to 60 minutes
from the default of 10 minutes.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/moby/commits/142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68"},{"sha":"56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Apply a 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size globally

This applies the 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size to not just `RUN` under
`docker build` (as was previously the case) but to `COPY` and `ADD`
under `docker build` and also to `docker run`.

It also removes an inconsistency that the 127GB size was not applied
when `--platform windows` was not passed to `docker build`, but WCOW was
still used as a platform default, e.g. Docker Desktop for Windows in
Windows Containers mode.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/moby/commits/56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296"},{"sha":"db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Parse storage-opt in GraphDriver init on Windows

This ensures the storage-opts applies to all operations by the graph
drivers, replacing the merging of storage-opts into container storage
config at container-creation time, and hence applying storage-opts to
non-container operations like `COPY` and `ADD` in the builder.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/moby/commits/db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32"},{"sha":"695b151a18299ade7c70dfe3babc8d77b7f5aba6","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Work around small disk on Windows-RS5 CI nodes

The free disk space on the Windows RS5 CI nodes appears to be just the
right size that the TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize test can generate 21GB of
layers, and then a 21GB sandbox inside a container, and then runs out of
space while committing the layer.

Helpfully, this failure is distinguishable in the logs from a failure
when the sandbox is too small, so we can do that.

TODO: Revert this if-and-when the Windows-RS5 CI nodes have more free
space.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/moby/commits/695b151a18299ade7c70dfe3babc8d77b7f5aba6"},{"sha":"1571e9331b4c56cc350bdf339b9aacd72eb3bbbd","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Use specific APIs for shared mount-point behaviour

[{"sha":"895ae67fd3cb16b23d66a8be2ad1c747188a811f","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Improve error boundary handling for unmounted subtrees (#20645)

A passive effect's cleanup function may throw after an unmount. Prior to this commit, such an error would be ignored. (React would not notify any error boundaries.)

After this commit, React will skip any unmounted boundaries and look for a still-mounted boundary. If one is found, it will call getDerivedStateFromError and/or componentDidCatch (depending on the type of boundary). Unmounted boundaries will be ignored, but as they have been unmounted– this seems appropriate.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/react/commits/895ae67fd3cb16b23d66a8be2ad1c747188a811f"},{"sha":"f0031dc6ed8801cc638c2f378911a93ceb8e2412","author":{"name":"Berton Zhu","email":"5ceac9ce76d89e1932a206e2c323e28ae20b5f68@126.com"},"message":"Devtool: `$r` should contain `hooks` property when it is forwardRef or memo component (#20626)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/react/commits/f0031dc6ed8801cc638c2f378911a93ceb8e2412"}]

PiperOrigin-RevId: 353677319
Change-Id: I3d0d7da8602ab45bbfa6fb23dc54b68cc7ea2ef7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/74e741619f700d8533d0925de5f566999a1ff62e"},{"sha":"fbf6fed2c7532fb673dcdbc97b28a1a8d13f8d0c","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"Refactor and speed up pylint code by ~15%.

Speed up from 177s to 152s.

Remove loop that was checking each error individually against allowlist regexps one by one. This is slow and also results in the same line being reported multiple times (e.g., for a total of 254 pylint reports, there are 1356 matches printed).

Furthermore, loop seems to have matched real errors against the approved list (because it takes regexps as words, not as lines! -- see below), thus allowing linting errors to pass through. Fixing them in this change too.

```
Found an allowlisted error:
  tensorflow/security/fuzzing/raggedCountSparseOutput_fuzz.py:36: [C0330(bad-continuation), ] Wrong hanging indentation (remove 6 spaces).
  via space
      ^^^^^ (this is a word in a allowlist line, taken as a regexp to match)
```

Display proper statistics about the errors at the end of the step.

Part of the work for #46046, #43040. Unblocks #46075

Change-Id: I3d0d7da8602ab45bbfa6fb23dc54b68cc7ea2ef7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PowerOlive/tensorflow/commits/74e741619f700d8533d0925de5f566999a1ff62e"},{"sha":"fbf6fed2c7532fb673dcdbc97b28a1a8d13f8d0c","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"Refactor and speed up pylint code by ~15%.

Speed up from 177s to 152s.

Remove loop that was checking each error individually against allowlist regexps one by one. This is slow and also results in the same line being reported multiple times (e.g., for a total of 254 pylint reports, there are 1356 matches printed).

Furthermore, loop seems to have matched real errors against the approved list (because it takes regexps as words, not as lines! -- see below), thus allowing linting errors to pass through. Fixing them in this change too.

```
Found an allowlisted error:
  tensorflow/security/fuzzing/raggedCountSparseOutput_fuzz.py:36: [C0330(bad-continuation), ] Wrong hanging indentation (remove 6 spaces).
  via space
      ^^^^^ (this is a word in a allowlist line, taken as a regexp to match)
```

Display proper statistics about the errors at the end of the step.

Part of the work for #46046, #43040. Unblocks #46075

`storage-opts` setting.

Sadly, this is a slow test, so we need to bump the timeout to 60 minutes
from the default of 10 minutes.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rizalgowandy/moby/commits/142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68"},{"sha":"56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Apply a 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size globally

This applies the 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size to not just `RUN` under
`docker build` (as was previously the case) but to `COPY` and `ADD`
under `docker build` and also to `docker run`.

It also removes an inconsistency that the 127GB size was not applied
when `--platform windows` was not passed to `docker build`, but WCOW was
still used as a platform default, e.g. Docker Desktop for Windows in
Windows Containers mode.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rizalgowandy/moby/commits/56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296"},{"sha":"db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Parse storage-opt in GraphDriver init on Windows

This ensures the storage-opts applies to all operations by the graph
drivers, replacing the merging of storage-opts into container storage
config at container-creation time, and hence applying storage-opts to
non-container operations like `COPY` and `ADD` in the builder.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rizalgowandy/moby/commits/db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32"},{"sha":"695b151a18299ade7c70dfe3babc8d77b7f5aba6","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Work around small disk on Windows-RS5 CI nodes

The free disk space on the Windows RS5 CI nodes appears to be just the
right size that the TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize test can generate 21GB of
layers, and then a 21GB sandbox inside a container, and then runs out of
space while committing the layer.

Helpfully, this failure is distinguishable in the logs from a failure
when the sandbox is too small, so we can do that.

TODO: Revert this if-and-when the Windows-RS5 CI nodes have more free
space.

## Motivation

An *interleaved* update is one that is scheduled while a render is
already in progress, typically from a concurrent user input event.

We have to take care not to process these updates during the current
render, because a multiple interleaved updates may have been scheduled
across many components; to avoid tearing, we cannot render some of
those updates without rendering all of them.

## Old approach

What we currently do when we detect an interleaved update is assign a
lane that is not part of the current render.

This has some unfortunate drawbacks. For example, we will eventually run
out of lanes at a given priority level. When this happens, our last
resort is to interrupt the current render and start over from scratch.
If this happens enough, it can lead to starvation.

More concerning, there are a suprising number of places that must
separately account for this case, often in subtle ways. The maintenance
complexity has led to a number of tearing bugs.

## New approach

I added a new field to the update queue, `interleaved`. It's a linked
list, just like the `pending` field. When an interleaved update is
scheduled, we add it to the `interleaved` list instead of `pending`.

Then we push the entire queue object onto a global array. When the
current render exits, we iterate through the array of interleaved queues
and transfer the `interleaved` list to the `pending` list.

So, until the current render has exited (whether due to a commit or an
interruption), it's impossible to process an interleaved update, because
they have not yet been enqueued.

In this new approach, we don't need to resort to clever lanes tricks to
avoid inconsistencies. This should allow us to simplify a lot of the
logic that's currently in ReactFiberWorkLoop and ReactFiberLane,
especially `findUpdateLane` and `getNextLanes`. All the logic for
interleaved updates is isolated to one place.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Andrew-Colman/react/commits/f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee"}]

[{"sha":"142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Add TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize integration test

This test validates that `RUN` and `COPY` both target a read-write
sandbox on Windows that is configured according to the daemon's
`storage-opts` setting.

Sadly, this is a slow test, so we need to bump the timeout to 60 minutes
from the default of 10 minutes.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MRS-OS/moby/commits/142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68"},{"sha":"56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Apply a 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size globally

This applies the 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size to not just `RUN` under
`docker build` (as was previously the case) but to `COPY` and `ADD`
under `docker build` and also to `docker run`.

It also removes an inconsistency that the 127GB size was not applied
when `--platform windows` was not passed to `docker build`, but WCOW was
still used as a platform default, e.g. Docker Desktop for Windows in
Windows Containers mode.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MRS-OS/moby/commits/56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296"},{"sha":"db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Parse storage-opt in GraphDriver init on Windows

This ensures the storage-opts applies to all operations by the graph
drivers, replacing the merging of storage-opts into container storage
config at container-creation time, and hence applying storage-opts to
non-container operations like `COPY` and `ADD` in the builder.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MRS-OS/moby/commits/db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32"},{"sha":"695b151a18299ade7c70dfe3babc8d77b7f5aba6","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Work around small disk on Windows-RS5 CI nodes

The free disk space on the Windows RS5 CI nodes appears to be just the
right size that the TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize test can generate 21GB of
layers, and then a 21GB sandbox inside a container, and then runs out of
space while committing the layer.

Helpfully, this failure is distinguishable in the logs from a failure
when the sandbox is too small, so we can do that.

TODO: Revert this if-and-when the Windows-RS5 CI nodes have more free
space.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MRS-OS/moby/commits/695b151a18299ade7c70dfe3babc8d77b7f5aba6"},{"sha":"1571e9331b4c56cc350bdf339b9aacd72eb3bbbd","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Use specific APIs for shared mount-point behaviour

PiperOrigin-RevId: 353677319
Change-Id: I3d0d7da8602ab45bbfa6fb23dc54b68cc7ea2ef7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/74e741619f700d8533d0925de5f566999a1ff62e"},{"sha":"fbf6fed2c7532fb673dcdbc97b28a1a8d13f8d0c","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"Refactor and speed up pylint code by ~15%.

Speed up from 177s to 152s.

Remove loop that was checking each error individually against allowlist regexps one by one. This is slow and also results in the same line being reported multiple times (e.g., for a total of 254 pylint reports, there are 1356 matches printed).

Furthermore, loop seems to have matched real errors against the approved list (because it takes regexps as words, not as lines! -- see below), thus allowing linting errors to pass through. Fixing them in this change too.

```
Found an allowlisted error:
  tensorflow/security/fuzzing/raggedCountSparseOutput_fuzz.py:36: [C0330(bad-continuation), ] Wrong hanging indentation (remove 6 spaces).
  via space
      ^^^^^ (this is a word in a allowlist line, taken as a regexp to match)
```

Display proper statistics about the errors at the end of the step.

Part of the work for #46046, #43040. Unblocks #46075

[{"sha":"142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Add TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize integration test

This test validates that `RUN` and `COPY` both target a read-write
sandbox on Windows that is configured according to the daemon's
`storage-opts` setting.

Sadly, this is a slow test, so we need to bump the timeout to 60 minutes
from the default of 10 minutes.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/meunice/moby/commits/142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68"},{"sha":"56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Apply a 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size globally

This applies the 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size to not just `RUN` under
`docker build` (as was previously the case) but to `COPY` and `ADD`
under `docker build` and also to `docker run`.

It also removes an inconsistency that the 127GB size was not applied
when `--platform windows` was not passed to `docker build`, but WCOW was
still used as a platform default, e.g. Docker Desktop for Windows in
Windows Containers mode.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/meunice/moby/commits/56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296"},{"sha":"db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Parse storage-opt in GraphDriver init on Windows

This ensures the storage-opts applies to all operations by the graph
drivers, replacing the merging of storage-opts into container storage
config at container-creation time, and hence applying storage-opts to
non-container operations like `COPY` and `ADD` in the builder.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/meunice/moby/commits/db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32"},{"sha":"695b151a18299ade7c70dfe3babc8d77b7f5aba6","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Work around small disk on Windows-RS5 CI nodes

The free disk space on the Windows RS5 CI nodes appears to be just the
right size that the TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize test can generate 21GB of
layers, and then a 21GB sandbox inside a container, and then runs out of
space while committing the layer.

Helpfully, this failure is distinguishable in the logs from a failure
when the sandbox is too small, so we can do that.

TODO: Revert this if-and-when the Windows-RS5 CI nodes have more free
space.

Change-Id: I3d0d7da8602ab45bbfa6fb23dc54b68cc7ea2ef7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/74e741619f700d8533d0925de5f566999a1ff62e"},{"sha":"fbf6fed2c7532fb673dcdbc97b28a1a8d13f8d0c","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"Refactor and speed up pylint code by ~15%.

Speed up from 177s to 152s.

Remove loop that was checking each error individually against allowlist regexps one by one. This is slow and also results in the same line being reported multiple times (e.g., for a total of 254 pylint reports, there are 1356 matches printed).

Furthermore, loop seems to have matched real errors against the approved list (because it takes regexps as words, not as lines! -- see below), thus allowing linting errors to pass through. Fixing them in this change too.

```
Found an allowlisted error:
  tensorflow/security/fuzzing/raggedCountSparseOutput_fuzz.py:36: [C0330(bad-continuation), ] Wrong hanging indentation (remove 6 spaces).
  via space
      ^^^^^ (this is a word in a allowlist line, taken as a regexp to match)
```

Display proper statistics about the errors at the end of the step.

Part of the work for #46046, #43040. Unblocks #46075

[{"sha":"142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Add TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize integration test

This test validates that `RUN` and `COPY` both target a read-write
sandbox on Windows that is configured according to the daemon's
`storage-opts` setting.

Sadly, this is a slow test, so we need to bump the timeout to 60 minutes
from the default of 10 minutes.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kaycoinsUSA/moby/commits/142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68"},{"sha":"56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Apply a 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size globally

This applies the 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size to not just `RUN` under
`docker build` (as was previously the case) but to `COPY` and `ADD`
under `docker build` and also to `docker run`.

It also removes an inconsistency that the 127GB size was not applied
when `--platform windows` was not passed to `docker build`, but WCOW was
still used as a platform default, e.g. Docker Desktop for Windows in
Windows Containers mode.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kaycoinsUSA/moby/commits/56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296"},{"sha":"db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Parse storage-opt in GraphDriver init on Windows

This ensures the storage-opts applies to all operations by the graph
drivers, replacing the merging of storage-opts into container storage
config at container-creation time, and hence applying storage-opts to
non-container operations like `COPY` and `ADD` in the builder.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kaycoinsUSA/moby/commits/db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32"},{"sha":"695b151a18299ade7c70dfe3babc8d77b7f5aba6","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Work around small disk on Windows-RS5 CI nodes

The free disk space on the Windows RS5 CI nodes appears to be just the
right size that the TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize test can generate 21GB of
layers, and then a 21GB sandbox inside a container, and then runs out of
space while committing the layer.

Helpfully, this failure is distinguishable in the logs from a failure
when the sandbox is too small, so we can do that.

TODO: Revert this if-and-when the Windows-RS5 CI nodes have more free
space.

[{"sha":"142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Add TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize integration test

This test validates that `RUN` and `COPY` both target a read-write
sandbox on Windows that is configured according to the daemon's
`storage-opts` setting.

Sadly, this is a slow test, so we need to bump the timeout to 60 minutes
from the default of 10 minutes.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/next-stack/moby/commits/142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68"},{"sha":"56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Apply a 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size globally

This applies the 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size to not just `RUN` under
`docker build` (as was previously the case) but to `COPY` and `ADD`
under `docker build` and also to `docker run`.

It also removes an inconsistency that the 127GB size was not applied
when `--platform windows` was not passed to `docker build`, but WCOW was
still used as a platform default, e.g. Docker Desktop for Windows in
Windows Containers mode.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/next-stack/moby/commits/56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296"},{"sha":"db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Parse storage-opt in GraphDriver init on Windows

This ensures the storage-opts applies to all operations by the graph
drivers, replacing the merging of storage-opts into container storage
config at container-creation time, and hence applying storage-opts to
non-container operations like `COPY` and `ADD` in the builder.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/next-stack/moby/commits/db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32"},{"sha":"695b151a18299ade7c70dfe3babc8d77b7f5aba6","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Work around small disk on Windows-RS5 CI nodes

The free disk space on the Windows RS5 CI nodes appears to be just the
right size that the TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize test can generate 21GB of
layers, and then a 21GB sandbox inside a container, and then runs out of
space while committing the layer.

Helpfully, this failure is distinguishable in the logs from a failure
when the sandbox is too small, so we can do that.

TODO: Revert this if-and-when the Windows-RS5 CI nodes have more free
space.

Speed up from 177s to 152s.

Remove loop that was checking each error individually against allowlist regexps one by one. This is slow and also results in the same line being reported multiple times (e.g., for a total of 254 pylint reports, there are 1356 matches printed).

Furthermore, loop seems to have matched real errors against the approved list (because it takes regexps as words, not as lines! -- see below), thus allowing linting errors to pass through. Fixing them in this change too.

```
Found an allowlisted error:
  tensorflow/security/fuzzing/raggedCountSparseOutput_fuzz.py:36: [C0330(bad-continuation), ] Wrong hanging indentation (remove 6 spaces).
  via space
      ^^^^^ (this is a word in a allowlist line, taken as a regexp to match)
```

Display proper statistics about the errors at the end of the step.

Part of the work for #46046, #43040. Unblocks #46075

Change-Id: I3d0d7da8602ab45bbfa6fb23dc54b68cc7ea2ef7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cache-Cloud/tensorflow/commits/74e741619f700d8533d0925de5f566999a1ff62e"},{"sha":"fbf6fed2c7532fb673dcdbc97b28a1a8d13f8d0c","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"Refactor and speed up pylint code by ~15%.

Speed up from 177s to 152s.

Remove loop that was checking each error individually against allowlist regexps one by one. This is slow and also results in the same line being reported multiple times (e.g., for a total of 254 pylint reports, there are 1356 matches printed).

Furthermore, loop seems to have matched real errors against the approved list (because it takes regexps as words, not as lines! -- see below), thus allowing linting errors to pass through. Fixing them in this change too.

```
Found an allowlisted error:
  tensorflow/security/fuzzing/raggedCountSparseOutput_fuzz.py:36: [C0330(bad-continuation), ] Wrong hanging indentation (remove 6 spaces).
  via space
      ^^^^^ (this is a word in a allowlist line, taken as a regexp to match)
```

Display proper statistics about the errors at the end of the step.

Part of the work for #46046, #43040. Unblocks #46075

[{"sha":"c32bdb4df77dda6a545c585431fa404b6a328506","author":{"name":"Harsha Vaidya","email":"7f61c6639c6fc9db938f6fcd93b2dec814161e8f@gmail.com"},"message":"fix(kumactl) de-duplicate passed env-vars (#1367)

When user supplies env-vars through kumactl, they are being added to the default list of env-vars instead of replacing them.
This fix makes sure the supplied env-vars get overridden properly if the env-var exists in default list otherwise they are added to the list.

* Create new template in _helpers.tpl and use it to generate env-vars in cp-deployment.yaml
* Update helmtemplates_vfsdata.go, since cp-deployment.yaml changed
* Update install-control-plane test cases, since generation of env-vars changed
* Add new test case in install-control-plane to test the fix

(#1448)

When specifying a `kuma.io/service` with a "." DNS resolution would not work
because it would only look at the first part of the DNS name.
This would also cause `foo.bar.mesh` and `foo.mesh` to resolve to the same thing
which may give a false sense of isolation of meshes in the DNS
We now only strips the last part of the DNS name if it matches the `.mesh` domain suffix.

[{"sha":"142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Add TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize integration test

This test validates that `RUN` and `COPY` both target a read-write
sandbox on Windows that is configured according to the daemon's
`storage-opts` setting.

Sadly, this is a slow test, so we need to bump the timeout to 60 minutes
from the default of 10 minutes.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/loot-king/moby/commits/142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68"},{"sha":"56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Apply a 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size globally

This applies the 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size to not just `RUN` under
`docker build` (as was previously the case) but to `COPY` and `ADD`
under `docker build` and also to `docker run`.

It also removes an inconsistency that the 127GB size was not applied
when `--platform windows` was not passed to `docker build`, but WCOW was
still used as a platform default, e.g. Docker Desktop for Windows in
Windows Containers mode.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/loot-king/moby/commits/56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296"},{"sha":"db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Parse storage-opt in GraphDriver init on Windows

This ensures the storage-opts applies to all operations by the graph
drivers, replacing the merging of storage-opts into container storage
config at container-creation time, and hence applying storage-opts to
non-container operations like `COPY` and `ADD` in the builder.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/loot-king/moby/commits/db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32"},{"sha":"695b151a18299ade7c70dfe3babc8d77b7f5aba6","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Work around small disk on Windows-RS5 CI nodes

The free disk space on the Windows RS5 CI nodes appears to be just the
right size that the TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize test can generate 21GB of
layers, and then a 21GB sandbox inside a container, and then runs out of
space while committing the layer.

Helpfully, this failure is distinguishable in the logs from a failure
when the sandbox is too small, so we can do that.

TODO: Revert this if-and-when the Windows-RS5 CI nodes have more free
space.

Change-Id: I3d0d7da8602ab45bbfa6fb23dc54b68cc7ea2ef7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/74e741619f700d8533d0925de5f566999a1ff62e"},{"sha":"fbf6fed2c7532fb673dcdbc97b28a1a8d13f8d0c","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"Refactor and speed up pylint code by ~15%.

Speed up from 177s to 152s.

Remove loop that was checking each error individually against allowlist regexps one by one. This is slow and also results in the same line being reported multiple times (e.g., for a total of 254 pylint reports, there are 1356 matches printed).

Furthermore, loop seems to have matched real errors against the approved list (because it takes regexps as words, not as lines! -- see below), thus allowing linting errors to pass through. Fixing them in this change too.

```
Found an allowlisted error:
  tensorflow/security/fuzzing/raggedCountSparseOutput_fuzz.py:36: [C0330(bad-continuation), ] Wrong hanging indentation (remove 6 spaces).
  via space
      ^^^^^ (this is a word in a allowlist line, taken as a regexp to match)
```

Display proper statistics about the errors at the end of the step.

Part of the work for #46046, #43040. Unblocks #46075

[{"sha":"f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Store interleaved updates on separate queue until end of render (#20615)

## Motivation

An *interleaved* update is one that is scheduled while a render is
already in progress, typically from a concurrent user input event.

We have to take care not to process these updates during the current
render, because a multiple interleaved updates may have been scheduled
across many components; to avoid tearing, we cannot render some of
those updates without rendering all of them.

## Old approach

What we currently do when we detect an interleaved update is assign a
lane that is not part of the current render.

This has some unfortunate drawbacks. For example, we will eventually run
out of lanes at a given priority level. When this happens, our last
resort is to interrupt the current render and start over from scratch.
If this happens enough, it can lead to starvation.

More concerning, there are a suprising number of places that must
separately account for this case, often in subtle ways. The maintenance
complexity has led to a number of tearing bugs.

## New approach

I added a new field to the update queue, `interleaved`. It's a linked
list, just like the `pending` field. When an interleaved update is
scheduled, we add it to the `interleaved` list instead of `pending`.

Then we push the entire queue object onto a global array. When the
current render exits, we iterate through the array of interleaved queues
and transfer the `interleaved` list to the `pending` list.

So, until the current render has exited (whether due to a commit or an
interruption), it's impossible to process an interleaved update, because
they have not yet been enqueued.

In this new approach, we don't need to resort to clever lanes tricks to
avoid inconsistencies. This should allow us to simplify a lot of the
logic that's currently in ReactFiberWorkLoop and ReactFiberLane,
especially `findUpdateLane` and `getNextLanes`. All the logic for
interleaved updates is isolated to one place.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bvaughn/react/commits/f15f8f64bbc3e02911d1a112fa9bb8f7066a56ee"},{"sha":"4b28e164f9df6899cb40bad224f9333c0ddf8100","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Improve error boundary handling for unmounted subtrees

[{"sha":"142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Add TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize integration test

This test validates that `RUN` and `COPY` both target a read-write
sandbox on Windows that is configured according to the daemon's
`storage-opts` setting.

Sadly, this is a slow test, so we need to bump the timeout to 60 minutes
from the default of 10 minutes.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bergwolf/moby/commits/142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68"},{"sha":"56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Apply a 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size globally

This applies the 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size to not just `RUN` under
`docker build` (as was previously the case) but to `COPY` and `ADD`
under `docker build` and also to `docker run`.

It also removes an inconsistency that the 127GB size was not applied
when `--platform windows` was not passed to `docker build`, but WCOW was
still used as a platform default, e.g. Docker Desktop for Windows in
Windows Containers mode.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bergwolf/moby/commits/56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296"},{"sha":"db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Parse storage-opt in GraphDriver init on Windows

This ensures the storage-opts applies to all operations by the graph
drivers, replacing the merging of storage-opts into container storage
config at container-creation time, and hence applying storage-opts to
non-container operations like `COPY` and `ADD` in the builder.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bergwolf/moby/commits/db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32"},{"sha":"695b151a18299ade7c70dfe3babc8d77b7f5aba6","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Work around small disk on Windows-RS5 CI nodes

The free disk space on the Windows RS5 CI nodes appears to be just the
right size that the TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize test can generate 21GB of
layers, and then a 21GB sandbox inside a container, and then runs out of
space while committing the layer.

Helpfully, this failure is distinguishable in the logs from a failure
when the sandbox is too small, so we can do that.

TODO: Revert this if-and-when the Windows-RS5 CI nodes have more free
space.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bergwolf/moby/commits/695b151a18299ade7c70dfe3babc8d77b7f5aba6"},{"sha":"1571e9331b4c56cc350bdf339b9aacd72eb3bbbd","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Use specific APIs for shared mount-point behaviour

[{"sha":"142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Add TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize integration test

This test validates that `RUN` and `COPY` both target a read-write
sandbox on Windows that is configured according to the daemon's
`storage-opts` setting.

Sadly, this is a slow test, so we need to bump the timeout to 60 minutes
from the default of 10 minutes.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/phiberoptick/moby/commits/142b2b785b4ee50f7d1998daa21230b51a3a6c68"},{"sha":"56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Apply a 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size globally

This applies the 127GB default WCOW Sandbox size to not just `RUN` under
`docker build` (as was previously the case) but to `COPY` and `ADD`
under `docker build` and also to `docker run`.

It also removes an inconsistency that the 127GB size was not applied
when `--platform windows` was not passed to `docker build`, but WCOW was
still used as a platform default, e.g. Docker Desktop for Windows in
Windows Containers mode.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/phiberoptick/moby/commits/56d378a88f27b42336d990764b3da9116584f296"},{"sha":"db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Parse storage-opt in GraphDriver init on Windows

This ensures the storage-opts applies to all operations by the graph
drivers, replacing the merging of storage-opts into container storage
config at container-creation time, and hence applying storage-opts to
non-container operations like `COPY` and `ADD` in the builder.

Signed-off-by: Paul "TBBle" Hampson <Paul.Hampson@Pobox.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/phiberoptick/moby/commits/db7b7f6df9151f0eca88af087514825b1a493f32"},{"sha":"695b151a18299ade7c70dfe3babc8d77b7f5aba6","author":{"name":"Paul "TBBle" Hampson","email":"220d126b3d70d9d7b0fda508e4cb236265bccc41@Pobox.com"},"message":"Work around small disk on Windows-RS5 CI nodes

The free disk space on the Windows RS5 CI nodes appears to be just the
right size that the TestBuildWCOWSandboxSize test can generate 21GB of
layers, and then a 21GB sandbox inside a container, and then runs out of
space while committing the layer.

Helpfully, this failure is distinguishable in the logs from a failure
when the sandbox is too small, so we can do that.

TODO: Revert this if-and-when the Windows-RS5 CI nodes have more free
space.

Speed up from 177s to 152s.

Remove loop that was checking each error individually against allowlist regexps one by one. This is slow and also results in the same line being reported multiple times (e.g., for a total of 254 pylint reports, there are 1356 matches printed).

Furthermore, loop seems to have matched real errors against the approved list (because it takes regexps as words, not as lines! -- see below), thus allowing linting errors to pass through. Fixing them in this change too.

```
Found an allowlisted error:
  tensorflow/security/fuzzing/raggedCountSparseOutput_fuzz.py:36: [C0330(bad-continuation), ] Wrong hanging indentation (remove 6 spaces).
  via space
      ^^^^^ (this is a word in a allowlist line, taken as a regexp to match)
```

Display proper statistics about the errors at the end of the step.

Part of the work for #46046, #43040. Unblocks #46075

```

Display proper statistics about the errors at the end of the step.

[{"sha":"895ae67fd3cb16b23d66a8be2ad1c747188a811f","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Improve error boundary handling for unmounted subtrees (#20645)

A passive effect's cleanup function may throw after an unmount. Prior to this commit, such an error would be ignored. (React would not notify any error boundaries.)

After this commit, React will skip any unmounted boundaries and look for a still-mounted boundary. If one is found, it will call getDerivedStateFromError and/or componentDidCatch (depending on the type of boundary). Unmounted boundaries will be ignored, but as they have been unmounted– this seems appropriate.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JCofman/react/commits/895ae67fd3cb16b23d66a8be2ad1c747188a811f"}]

Change-Id: I3d0d7da8602ab45bbfa6fb23dc54b68cc7ea2ef7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/74e741619f700d8533d0925de5f566999a1ff62e"},{"sha":"fbf6fed2c7532fb673dcdbc97b28a1a8d13f8d0c","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"Refactor and speed up pylint code by ~15%.

Speed up from 177s to 152s.

Remove loop that was checking each error individually against allowlist regexps one by one. This is slow and also results in the same line being reported multiple times (e.g., for a total of 254 pylint reports, there are 1356 matches printed).

Furthermore, loop seems to have matched real errors against the approved list (because it takes regexps as words, not as lines! -- see below), thus allowing linting errors to pass through. Fixing them in this change too.

```
Found an allowlisted error:
  tensorflow/security/fuzzing/raggedCountSparseOutput_fuzz.py:36: [C0330(bad-continuation), ] Wrong hanging indentation (remove 6 spaces).
  via space
      ^^^^^ (this is a word in a allowlist line, taken as a regexp to match)
```

Display proper statistics about the errors at the end of the step.

Part of the work for #46046, #43040. Unblocks #46075

Change-Id: I3d0d7da8602ab45bbfa6fb23dc54b68cc7ea2ef7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/74e741619f700d8533d0925de5f566999a1ff62e"},{"sha":"fbf6fed2c7532fb673dcdbc97b28a1a8d13f8d0c","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"Refactor and speed up pylint code by ~15%.

Speed up from 177s to 152s.

Remove loop that was checking each error individually against allowlist regexps one by one. This is slow and also results in the same line being reported multiple times (e.g., for a total of 254 pylint reports, there are 1356 matches printed).

Furthermore, loop seems to have matched real errors against the approved list (because it takes regexps as words, not as lines! -- see below), thus allowing linting errors to pass through. Fixing them in this change too.

```
Found an allowlisted error:
  tensorflow/security/fuzzing/raggedCountSparseOutput_fuzz.py:36: [C0330(bad-continuation), ] Wrong hanging indentation (remove 6 spaces).
  via space
      ^^^^^ (this is a word in a allowlist line, taken as a regexp to match)
```

Display proper statistics about the errors at the end of the step.

Part of the work for #46046, #43040. Unblocks #46075

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/afe1e4e9a1d4ef1b06bf96e9351f1a9e70f1029a"},{"sha":"f4b686b5f3db28f09d2561eb2aee3e1c3a9bf270","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26614 from hashicorp/jbardin/0.14-26606

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

Note that we do not suppress logs if connection info contains sensitive
information, as provisioners should not be logging connection
information under any circumstances.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/47f8ed4cd62068332eca4d1903b7dfaf6064adc4"},{"sha":"2b485cd4284725396abe26b5ae0175659199e78a","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"website: Sensitive values in provisioner config","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/2b485cd4284725396abe26b5ae0175659199e78a"},{"sha":"a18415686b40d89406992d5d300dc02566a91c4c","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26630 from hashicorp/alisdair/sensitive-values-provisioners-014

The Legacy SDK cannot handle missing strings from objects in sets, and
will insert an empty string when planning the missing value. This
subverts the `couldHaveUnknownBlockPlaceholder` check, and causes
errors when `dynamic` is used with NestingSet blocks.

We don't have a separate codepath to handle the internals of
AssertObjectCompatible differently for the legacy SDK, but we can treat
empty strings as null strings within set objects to avoid the failed
assertions.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/060f8acc081c9be2ef5b2d0277742ea753615ee2"},{"sha":"527f3e654cfd2417410ae4bdeffecfa53d28ea7b","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26641 from hashicorp/jbardin/backport-26638

If provisioner configuration or connection info includes sensitive
values, we need to unmark them before calling the provisioner. Failing
to do so causes serialization to error.

Unlike resources, we do not need to capture marked paths here, so we
just discard the marks.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/9c580335e303610f96e01cfa8859ea6ee78ea87e"},{"sha":"4f53234d8cf6c9f964ac8bfa8bce3a624a119bf1","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"terraform: Hide maybe-sensitive provisioner output

If the provisioner configuration includes sensitive values, it's a
reasonable assumption that we should suppress its log output. Obvious
examples where this makes sense include echoing a secret to a file using
local-exec or remote-exec.

This commit adds tests for both logging output from provisioners with
non-sensitive configuration, and suppressing logs for provisioners with
sensitive values in configuration.

Note that we do not suppress logs if connection info contains sensitive
information, as provisioners should not be logging connection
information under any circumstances.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/4f53234d8cf6c9f964ac8bfa8bce3a624a119bf1"},{"sha":"e3804810a9c95fe590f6eb3807a12d86a0ecf76e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Accept JSON encoded dynamic values from providers

Core was previously ignoring JSON-encoded dynamic values, but these are
technically supported, so we must either error or accept the value.
Since we already have the decoder for Json state, it's minimal effort to
support this on all plugin methods too.

This change also gives providers an easy way to implement the
UpgradeResourceState method. The obvious implementation of returning the same
JSON-encoded value has tripped up a few providers not using the legacy
SDK already, and we should have at least indicated that the value was
being lost.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/e3804810a9c95fe590f6eb3807a12d86a0ecf76e"},{"sha":"98dc3990628bb94f5877cd04e1cf56851ba8a7bb","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #26606 from hashicorp/jbardin/proposed-set-comparison

More precise handling of lists and maps within sets for ProposedNewObject","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/98dc3990628bb94f5877cd04e1cf56851ba8a7bb"},{"sha":"30204ecded21fb52c992b0a707bb4cbb96e2c608","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command/cliconfig: Allow development overrides for providers

For normal provider installation we want to associate each provider with
a selected version number and find a suitable package for that version
that conforms to the official hashes for that release.

Those requirements are very onerous for a provider developer currently
testing a not-yet-released build, though. To allow for that case this new
CLI configuration feature allows overriding specific providers to refer
to give local filesystem directories.

Any provider overridden in this way is not subject to the usual
restrictions about selected versions or checksum conformance, and
activating an override won't cause any changes to the selections recorded
in the lock file because it's intended to be a temporary setting for one
developer only.

This is, in a sense, a spiritual successor of an old capability we had to
override specific plugins in the CLI configuration file. There were
some vestiges of that left in the main package and CLI config package
but nothing has actually been honoring them for several versions now and
so this commit removes them to avoid confusion with the new mechanism.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/30204ecded21fb52c992b0a707bb4cbb96e2c608"}]

Change-Id: I3d0d7da8602ab45bbfa6fb23dc54b68cc7ea2ef7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/74e741619f700d8533d0925de5f566999a1ff62e"},{"sha":"fbf6fed2c7532fb673dcdbc97b28a1a8d13f8d0c","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"Refactor and speed up pylint code by ~15%.

Speed up from 177s to 152s.

Remove loop that was checking each error individually against allowlist regexps one by one. This is slow and also results in the same line being reported multiple times (e.g., for a total of 254 pylint reports, there are 1356 matches printed).

Furthermore, loop seems to have matched real errors against the approved list (because it takes regexps as words, not as lines! -- see below), thus allowing linting errors to pass through. Fixing them in this change too.

```
Found an allowlisted error:
  tensorflow/security/fuzzing/raggedCountSparseOutput_fuzz.py:36: [C0330(bad-continuation), ] Wrong hanging indentation (remove 6 spaces).
  via space
      ^^^^^ (this is a word in a allowlist line, taken as a regexp to match)
```

Display proper statistics about the errors at the end of the step.

Part of the work for #46046, #43040. Unblocks #46075

PiperOrigin-RevId: 353677319
Change-Id: I3d0d7da8602ab45bbfa6fb23dc54b68cc7ea2ef7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Nicholas282787728/tensorflow/commits/74e741619f700d8533d0925de5f566999a1ff62e"},{"sha":"fbf6fed2c7532fb673dcdbc97b28a1a8d13f8d0c","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"Refactor and speed up pylint code by ~15%.

Speed up from 177s to 152s.

Remove loop that was checking each error individually against allowlist regexps one by one. This is slow and also results in the same line being reported multiple times (e.g., for a total of 254 pylint reports, there are 1356 matches printed).

Furthermore, loop seems to have matched real errors against the approved list (because it takes regexps as words, not as lines! -- see below), thus allowing linting errors to pass through. Fixing them in this change too.

```
Found an allowlisted error:
  tensorflow/security/fuzzing/raggedCountSparseOutput_fuzz.py:36: [C0330(bad-continuation), ] Wrong hanging indentation (remove 6 spaces).
  via space
      ^^^^^ (this is a word in a allowlist line, taken as a regexp to match)
```

Display proper statistics about the errors at the end of the step.

Part of the work for #46046, #43040. Unblocks #46075
